Questions:
What will happen if you choose to withdraw from the research study at any time?
A) You will be required to pay a penalty fee for early withdrawal; 
B) Your medical care or benefits at MUSC will be negatively affected; 
C) You will still be responsible for any services rendered up to the point of withdrawal; 
D) Your decision to withdraw will not affect your current or future medical care or benefits at MUSC.

Correct answer: D

Which of the following interventions is considered experimental in this study for head and neck cancer survivors?
A) Standard medical treatment for head and neck cancer;
B) Routine clinical care and follow-up appointments;
C) Brief Tele-Cognitive Behavioral Therapy Intervention (BRIGHT) via video telemedicine;
D) Educational sessions on general health maintenance.

Correct answer: C

What is the alternative to participating in the BRIGHT study for head and neck cancer survivors with body image concerns?
A) Undergoing standard chemotherapy treatment; 
B) Choosing not to participate in the study without any consequences to standard care; 
C) Receiving a different form of psychotherapy not offered in the study; 
D) Being automatically enrolled in another unrelated clinical trial.

Correct answer: B

If you experience any discomfort or have concerns about your rights as a research subject during the study, whom should you contact?

A) The study sponsor's customer service hotline;
B) The MUSC Institutional Review Board for Human Research IRB Manager or the Office of Research Integrity Director;
C) A healthcare provider unrelated to the study;
D) Your local member of Congress.

Correct answer: B) The MUSC Institutional Review Board for Human Research IRB Manager or the Office of Research Integrity Director.
